    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 30 with a roster optimized for speed-dependent scoring, though the schedule presents significant friction today. **Corbin Carroll** secures the highest efficiency score at 59.06, buoyed by a substantial +10% boost from favorable platoon dynamics and his elite propensity to capitalize on slow-working starters like Woodruff. While the -19% penalty for facing an elite-tier arm remains a concern, the projection model favors **Corbin Carroll** as our primary engine today. **James Wood** (55.45) follows closely; despite a tough assignment against a fast-throwing Peralta, his role at the top of the lineup and the potential for a stolen base against a slow delivery keep his floor elevated. **Brice Turang** (58.33) remains a vital asset in this 5x5 build, as his position in the #2 hole and a favorable matchup against Soroka provide the most reliable path to R and SB production across our active core.\n\nOur decision-making process was challenged by **Kyle Karros** (56.32), who earned a spot primarily due to a +5% wind-out factor and a strong platoon edge against Abbott. **Austin Riley** (51.50) is the most marginal start of the group; he faces the formidable Valdez, F, and while his +2% adjustment for the pitcher's delivery speed keeps him viable, his lack of high-end stolen base potential makes him the most vulnerable to a negative outcome should he fail to contribute to our HR or RBI totals. With **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Josh Naylor** all sitting due to schedule gaps, our remaining depth\u2014including **Mickey Moniak**, **Trevor Story**, **Seiya Suzuki**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Vinnie Pasquantino**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, **Max Muncy**, **Gabriel Moreno**, **Carson Williams**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Dalton Rushing**, **Luis Campusano**, **Alex Freeland**, and **Travis Bazzana**\u2014offered no viable high-floor pivots that could outperform the projected efficiency of the starters. We are essentially riding our thin core through a difficult day of opposing pitching, prioritizing SB-centric profiles over raw power until our full bench availability returns.",
